%N A389792 Total number of ascents in all heapable permutations of length n.
%C A389792 A permutation of [1..n] is heapable if it can be inserted, one element at a time, into a binary min-heap without violating the heap property.
%C A389792 An ascent in a permutation p is an index i with 1<=i<=n-1 such that p(i)<p(i+1).
%H A389792 Benjamin Chen, Michael Cho, Mario Tutuncu-Macias, and Tony Tzolov, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.dam.2023.01.025">Efficient methods of calculating the number of heapable permutations</a>, Discrete Applied Mathematics Volume 331, 31 May 2023, Pages 126-137.
%H A389792 Manolopoulos Panagiotis, <a href="/A389792/a389792.py.txt">Python program</a>
%F A389792 a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n-1} k*A389255(n,k+1).
%e A389792 For n=4, the heapable permutations are:
%e A389792   (1,2,3,4): ascents at positions (1,2),(2,3),(3,4)  3 ascents.
%e A389792   (1,3,2,4): ascents at (1,3),(2,4)  2 ascents.
%e A389792   (1,2,4,3): ascents at (1,2),(2,4)  2 ascents.
%e A389792   (1,4,2,3): ascents at (1,4),(2,3)  2 ascents.
%e A389792   (1,3,4,2): ascents at (1,3),(3,4)  2 ascents.
%e A389792 So the total number of ascents across all 5 heapable permutations of length 4 is: 3+2+2+2+2 = 11.
